Bluetongue, Botswana
--------------------
Information received on [and dated] 26 Aug 2014 from Letlhogile Modisa, Director, Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Gaborone, Botswana

Summary:
Report type: immediate notification (final report)
Date of start of the event: 24 Feb 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 11 Jul 2014
Report date: 26 Aug 2014
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 31 Jan 2008
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Bluetongue virus
Serotype: not typed
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Moselele, Molepolole, Kweneng, Kweneng
Date of start of the outbreak: 24 Feb 2014
Outbreak status: resolved (26 Aug 2014)
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Sheep/ 40 / 2 / 0 / 0 / 2
Affected population: sheep reared in a communal setup

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Sheep / 5 / 0 / 0 / 5
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comment: 2 sheep in a flock of 40 showed clinical signs consistent with bluetongue. Samples taken tested positive for bluetongue virus antibodies. There have been no other cases since February 2014. This event is closed.

Control measures
Measures applied: no vaccination; treatment of affected animals (antibiotics for secondary infection)
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Botswana National Veterinary Laboratory (national laboratory) / Sheep / indirect ELISA / 11 Jul 2014 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

